		</li>
		<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 155px">
			<div class="thumb" style="width: 150px; height: 150px;"><span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Temple_of_the_Tooth,_Kandy_0515.jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2f/Temple_of_the_Tooth%2C_Kandy_0515.jpg/120px-Temple_of_the_Tooth%2C_Kandy_0515.jpg" decoding="async" width="120" height="90" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2f/Temple_of_the_Tooth%2C_Kandy_0515.jpg/180px-Temple_of_the_Tooth%2C_Kandy_0515.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2f/Temple_of_the_Tooth%2C_Kandy_0515.jpg/240px-Temple_of_the_Tooth%2C_Kandy_0515.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2592" data-file-height="1944" /></a></span></div>
			<div class="gallerytext"></div>
		</li>
		<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 155px">
			<div class="thumb" style="width: 150px; height: 150px;"><span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Temple_of_the_Tooth,_Kandy_0518.jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ee/Temple_of_the_Tooth%2C_Kandy_0518.jpg/90px-Temple_of_the_Tooth%2C_Kandy_0518.jpg" decoding="async" width="90" height="120" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ee/Temple_of_the_Tooth%2C_Kandy_0518.jpg/135px-Temple_of_the_Tooth%2C_Kandy_0518.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ee/Temple_of_the_Tooth%2C_Kandy_0518.jpg/180px-Temple_of_the_Tooth%2C_Kandy_0518.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1944" data-file-height="2592" /></a></span></div>
			<div class="gallerytext"></div>
		</li>
</ul>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Dance">Dance</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kingdom_of_Kandy&amp;action=edit&amp;section=24" title="Edit section: Dance"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Kandyan art is also known for being very detailed and beautiful. One example is <a href="/wiki/Kandyan_dance" title="Kandyan dance">Kandyan dancing</a>, which is known for its flowing movements and bright costumes. People often perform Kandyan dancing at special events and it's an important part of Sri Lankan culture.
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Jewellery">Jewellery</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kingdom_of_Kandy&amp;action=edit&amp;section=25" title="Edit section: Jewellery"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Another important art form is <a href="/wiki/Kandyan_jewellery" title="Kandyan jewellery">Kandyan jewelry-making.</a> The jewelers make very detailed designs with precious stones and metals. People in the Kandyan royal court used to wear this jewelry to show their wealth and status.
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Architecture">Architecture</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kingdom_of_Kandy&amp;action=edit&amp;section=26" title="Edit section: Architecture"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Kandyan architecture was the style of architecture used in the Kandyan kingdom. This style was heavily influenced by the architecture of the Malabar region in South India, due to the close connection between the two regions during that time. Unlike stone, wood was the main building material used in Kandyan architecture, which was a reflection of the architectural practices of Malabar.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_46-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-46">&#91;46&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<figure class="mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:SL_Kandy_asv2020-01_img35_Sacred_Tooth_Temple.jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b6/SL_Kandy_asv2020-01_img35_Sacred_Tooth_Temple.jpg/250px-SL_Kandy_asv2020-01_img35_Sacred_Tooth_Temple.jpg" decoding="async" width="250" height="167" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b6/SL_Kandy_asv2020-01_img35_Sacred_Tooth_Temple.jpg/375px-SL_Kandy_asv2020-01_img35_Sacred_Tooth_Temple.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b6/SL_Kandy_asv2020-01_img35_Sacred_Tooth_Temple.jpg/500px-SL_Kandy_asv2020-01_img35_Sacred_Tooth_Temple.jpg 2x" data-file-width="7720" data-file-height="5147" /></a><figcaption>Interior of the <a href="/wiki/Temple_of_the_Tooth" title="Temple of the Tooth">Temple of the Tooth</a>, Kandy. Successive kings expanded and improved the temple throughout the Kandyan kingdom's existence.</figcaption></figure><p>
The audience hall is a great example of how Kandyan architecture adapted to its environment. The structure was supported by intricately carved wooden pillars that were later replicated in stone at the Dalada Maligava. Additionally, Kandyan architecture featured long verandahs supported by pillars made of various materials, including wood, stone, or masonry. These structures had peaked roofs and overhanging eaves to protect the walls from the elements. The Lankatilaka vihara is a prime example of this style.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_46-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-46">&#91;46&#93;</a></sup></p><ul class="gallery mw-gallery-traditional">
		<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 155px">
			<div class="thumb" style="width: 150px; height: 150px;"><span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Lankathilaka_Viharaya_59.JPG" class="mw-file-description" title="Lankathilaka Viharaya"><img alt="Lankathilaka Viharaya" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/24/Lankathilaka_Viharaya_59.JPG/120px-Lankathilaka_Viharaya_59.JPG" decoding="async" width="120" height="90" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/24/Lankathilaka_Viharaya_59.JPG/180px-Lankathilaka_Viharaya_59.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/24/Lankathilaka_Viharaya_59.JPG/240px-Lankathilaka_Viharaya_59.JPG 2x" data-file-width="2592" data-file-height="1944" /></a></span></div>
			<div class="gallerytext">Lankathilaka Viharaya</div>
		</li>
		<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 155px">
			<div class="thumb" style="width: 150px; height: 150px;"><span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Lankathilaka_Viharaya_90.JPG" class="mw-file-description" title="Lankathilaka Viharaya Entrance"><img alt="Lankathilaka Viharaya Entrance" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/58/Lankathilaka_Viharaya_90.JPG/90px-Lankathilaka_Viharaya_90.JPG" decoding="async" width="90" height="120" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/58/Lankathilaka_Viharaya_90.JPG/135px-Lankathilaka_Viharaya_90.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/58/Lankathilaka_Viharaya_90.JPG/180px-Lankathilaka_Viharaya_90.JPG 2x" data-file-width="1944" data-file-height="2592" /></a></span></div>
			<div class="gallerytext">Lankathilaka Viharaya Entrance</div>
		</li>
		<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 155px">
			<div class="thumb" style="width: 150px; height: 150px;"><span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Sri_Dalada_Maligawa-20-kandy-Sri_Lanka.jpg" class="mw-file-description" title="The audience hall of Kandyan Royal Palace"><img alt="The audience hall of Kandyan Royal Palace" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c4/Sri_Dalada_Maligawa-20-kandy-Sri_Lanka.jpg/120px-Sri_Dalada_Maligawa-20-kandy-Sri_Lanka.jpg" decoding="async" width="120" height="90" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c4/Sri_Dalada_Maligawa-20-kandy-Sri_Lanka.jpg/180px-Sri_Dalada_Maligawa-20-kandy-Sri_Lanka.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c4/Sri_Dalada_Maligawa-20-kandy-Sri_Lanka.jpg/240px-Sri_Dalada_Maligawa-20-kandy-Sri_Lanka.jpg 2x" data-file-width="4608" data-file-height="3456" /></a></span></div>
			<div class="gallerytext">The audience hall of Kandyan Royal Palace</div>
		</li>
		<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 155px">
			<div class="thumb" style="width: 150px; height: 150px;"><span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Gadaladeniya_Viharaya_61.JPG" class="mw-file-description" title="Gadaladeniya Viharaya Dagaba"><img alt="Gadaladeniya Viharaya Dagaba" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/58/Gadaladeniya_Viharaya_61.JPG/120px-Gadaladeniya_Viharaya_61.JPG" decoding="async" width="120" height="90" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/58/Gadaladeniya_Viharaya_61.JPG/180px-Gadaladeniya_Viharaya_61.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/58/Gadaladeniya_Viharaya_61.JPG/240px-Gadaladeniya_Viharaya_61.JPG 2x" data-file-width="2592" data-file-height="1944" /></a></span></div>
			<div class="gallerytext">Gadaladeniya Viharaya Dagaba</div>
		</li>
		<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 155px">
			<div class="thumb" style="width: 150px; height: 150px;"><span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Old_photo_of_the_maha_wasala.jpg" class="mw-file-description" title="Old photo of King&#39;s Quarters in Kandyan Royal palace"><img alt="Old photo of King&#39;s Quarters in Kandyan Royal palace" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c5/Old_photo_of_the_maha_wasala.jpg/120px-Old_photo_of_the_maha_wasala.jpg" decoding="async" width="120" height="80" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c5/Old_photo_of_the_maha_wasala.jpg/180px-Old_photo_of_the_maha_wasala.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c5/Old_photo_of_the_maha_wasala.jpg/240px-Old_photo_of_the_maha_wasala.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3960" data-file-height="2640" /></a></span></div>
			<div class="gallerytext">Old photo of King's Quarters in Kandyan Royal palace</div>
		</li>
		<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 155px">
			<div class="thumb" style="width: 150px; height: 150px;"><span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Kandy_Sri_Lanka_Temple_of_the_tooth.jpg" class="mw-file-description" title="The Octagonal Pavilion in Kandyan Royal palace"><img alt="The Octagonal Pavilion in Kandyan Royal palace" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6f/Kandy_Sri_Lanka_Temple_of_the_tooth.jpg/120px-Kandy_Sri_Lanka_Temple_of_the_tooth.jpg" decoding="async" width="120" height="80" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6f/Kandy_Sri_Lanka_Temple_of_the_tooth.jpg/180px-Kandy_Sri_Lanka_Temple_of_the_tooth.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6f/Kandy_Sri_Lanka_Temple_of_the_tooth.jpg/240px-Kandy_Sri_Lanka_Temple_of_the_tooth.jpg 2x" data-file-width="5184" data-file-height="3456" /></a></span></div>
			<div class="gallerytext">The Octagonal Pavilion in Kandyan Royal palace</div>
		</li>
</ul>
<p>Kandyan architects played a vital role in the development of Buddhist architecture by introducing Tampita viharages. These image-houses were constructed on raised platforms and became a prominent aspect of Kandyan Buddhist temples. Typically, these temples featured a pansala for bhikkhus to reside, a vihara for the image-house, and a stupa or dagoba. However, some temples did not have a dagoba. Furthermore, nearly every temple had a devale, which was a shrine dedicated to a Hindu deity. The statue of the Hindu god was usually housed under the same roof as the Buddha's statue.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_46-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-46">&#91;46&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<figure typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Atrium_in_Maduwanwela_Walawwa_-_%E0%B6%B8%E0%B6%A9%E0%B7%94%E0%B7%80%E0%B6%B1%E0%B7%8A%E0%B7%80%E0%B7%99%E0%B6%BD_%E0%B7%80%E0%B6%BD%E0%B7%80%E0%B7%8A%E0%B7%80_2012_-_panoramio.jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8e/Atrium_in_Maduwanwela_Walawwa_-_%E0%B6%B8%E0%B6%A9%E0%B7%94%E0%B7%80%E0%B6%B1%E0%B7%8A%E0%B7%80%E0%B7%99%E0%B6%BD_%E0%B7%80%E0%B6%BD%E0%B7%80%E0%B7%8A%E0%B7%80_2012_-_panoramio.jpg/250px-Atrium_in_Maduwanwela_Walawwa_-_%E0%B6%B8%E0%B6%A9%E0%B7%94%E0%B7%80%E0%B6%B1%E0%B7%8A%E0%B7%80%E0%B7%99%E0%B6%BD_%E0%B7%80%E0%B6%BD%E0%B7%80%E0%B7%8A%E0%B7%80_2012_-_panoramio.jpg" decoding="async" width="250" height="188" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8e/Atrium_in_Maduwanwela_Walawwa_-_%E0%B6%B8%E0%B6%A9%E0%B7%94%E0%B7%80%E0%B6%B1%E0%B7%8A%E0%B7%80%E0%B7%99%E0%B6%BD_%E0%B7%80%E0%B6%BD%E0%B7%80%E0%B7%8A%E0%B7%80_2012_-_panoramio.jpg/375px-Atrium_in_Maduwanwela_Walawwa_-_%E0%B6%B8%E0%B6%A9%E0%B7%94%E0%B7%80%E0%B6%B1%E0%B7%8A%E0%B7%80%E0%B7%99%E0%B6%BD_%E0%B7%80%E0%B6%BD%E0%B7%80%E0%B7%8A%E0%B7%80_2012_-_panoramio.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8e/Atrium_in_Maduwanwela_Walawwa_-_%E0%B6%B8%E0%B6%A9%E0%B7%94%E0%B7%80%E0%B6%B1%E0%B7%8A%E0%B7%80%E0%B7%99%E0%B6%BD_%E0%B7%80%E0%B6%BD%E0%B7%80%E0%B7%8A%E0%B7%80_2012_-_panoramio.jpg/500px-Atrium_in_Maduwanwela_Walawwa_-_%E0%B6%B8%E0%B6%A9%E0%B7%94%E0%B7%80%E0%B6%B1%E0%B7%8A%E0%B7%80%E0%B7%99%E0%B6%BD_%E0%B7%80%E0%B6%BD%E0%B7%80%E0%B7%8A%E0%B7%80_2012_-_panoramio.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3296" data-file-height="2472" /></a><figcaption>A central courtyard in Maduwanwela Walawwa</figcaption></figure>
<p>The residences of the common people were modest, consisting of one-story buildings, and the most basic ones having only a solitary room. These abodes consisted of mud walls built around a wooden frame, thatched roofs, and polished floors made by blending mud and cow-dung. The upper class lived in more refined structures called Walawwas, which often had unpolished windows on the interior walls. The rooms in Walawwas were usually organized around a central courtyard known as "hataras midula," which remained uncovered to the sky.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_46-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-46">&#91;46&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>During the Kandyan kingdom, the sculpture art was considered less impressive than the Anuradhapura and Polonnaruva periods. This is especially evident in the moonstones that were created during that time. The moonstones lost their symbolic significance and were reduced to mere decorations featuring various shapes and designs. The moonstones found at Dalada Maligava are a prime example of this as they have elongated ends and are highly conventionalized. It is worth noting that there is no direct artistic connection between the traditions of Sigiri, Polonnaruva, and the Kandyan kingdom.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_46-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-46">&#91;46&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul class="gallery mw-gallery-traditional">
		<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 155px">
			<div class="thumb" style="width: 150px; height: 150px;"><span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Head_of_a_Bodhisattva_LACMA_M.78.30.jpg" class="mw-file-description" title="16th-century Kandy period sculpture at Mahavihara Bingiriya, crafted from stucco and adorned with paint"><img alt="16th-century Kandy period sculpture at Mahavihara Bingiriya, crafted from stucco and adorned with paint" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/05/Head_of_a_Bodhisattva_LACMA_M.78.30.jpg/66px-Head_of_a_Bodhisattva_LACMA_M.78.30.jpg" decoding="async" width="66" height="120" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/05/Head_of_a_Bodhisattva_LACMA_M.78.30.jpg/99px-Head_of_a_Bodhisattva_LACMA_M.78.30.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/05/Head_of_a_Bodhisattva_LACMA_M.78.30.jpg/133px-Head_of_a_Bodhisattva_LACMA_M.78.30.jpg 2x" data-file-width="354" data-file-height="640" /></a></span></div>
